{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17525303","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17525303"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T15:14:30+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T15:14:30+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14074"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14074","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14074"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.08,0.42,0.36,0.05,0.09]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6740"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114919"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6740","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6740"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14074"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96925"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"12"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"115"},{"type":"tags","id":"2899"},{"type":"tags","id":"4919"},{"type":"tags","id":"4974"},{"type":"tags","id":"11633"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"14532"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14533"},{"type":"contributions","id":"40749"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43475"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114919","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/114919"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 60-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a history of finger colour changes in response to cold temperatures for many years. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. On examination, her vital signs are within normal limits. An image of her face is seen below (Image). Investigations reveal negative dsDNA antibodies.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following investigations is LEAST likely to have a role in evaluating extra-articular manifestations of this condition?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Pulmonary function tests","Right heart catheterisation","Endoscopic ultrasound","High-resolution CT chest","Transthoracic echocardiogram"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe clinical presentation described is consistent with systemic sclerosis (scleroderma). The patient presents with a long history of Raynaud\u0027s phenomenon and characteristic facial skin changes, including skin tightening and perioral radial furrowing (referred to as \u0027scleroderma-like facies\u0027, avoid use of the historical term \u0027bird-like facies\u0027). The negative dsDNA antibodies help to differentiate this condition from systemic lupus erythematosus.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEndoscopic ultrasound\u003C/strong\u003E is the least likely investigation to be used in evaluating extra-articular manifestations of systemic sclerosis. While gastrointestinal involvement is common in systemic sclerosis, endoscopic ultrasound is not routinely used for its evaluation. Instead, other tests such as barium swallow, esophageal manometry, or standard endoscopy are more commonly employed. Endoscopic ultrasound has more of a role in conditions such as inflammatory bowel disease.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPulmonary function tests\u003C/strong\u003E are crucial in assessing lung involvement in systemic sclerosis. They may reveal a restrictive pattern suggestive of interstitial lung disease, a common complication of the disease. \u003Cstrong\u003EHigh-resolution CT chest\u003C/strong\u003E are similarly essential for detecting and monitoring interstitial lung disease, which occurs in many patients with systemic sclerosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETransthoracic echocardiogram\u003C/strong\u003E is used to screen for pulmonary hypertension and assess cardiac function, as systemic sclerosis can affect the heart, leading to conditions such as pericardial effusion or myocardial fibrosis. \u003Cstrong\u003ERight heart catheterisation\u003C/strong\u003E is the gold standard for diagnosing pulmonary arterial hypertension, a serious complication of systemic sclerosis that affects approximately 10% of patients.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Systemic sclerosis can present with Raynaud\u0027s phenomenon and characteristic facial skin changes.","Pulmonary, cardiac, and gastrointestinal involvement are common extra-articular manifestations of systemic sclerosis."],"references":["Adigun R, Goyal A, Bansal P, Hariz A. Systemic Sclerosis (CREST syndrome).  In: StatPearls [online]. 2020. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK430875/","Bobeica C, Niculet E, Craescu M, Parapiru EL, Musat CL, Dinu C, et al. CREST Syndrome in Systemic Sclerosis Patients - Is Dystrophic Calcinosis a Key Element to a Positive Diagnosis? J Inflamm Res. 2022 Jun 9;15:3387-3394. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC9191197/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96925"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14074"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"22128"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"22128","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/22128"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/z8lcUtoVz8mS84a5xNUxLWMN15SdIt.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/z8lcUtoVz8mS84a5xNUxLWMN15SdIt.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":800,"height":557}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96925","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/96925"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-21T13:57:57+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-21